{{Infobox book | name = Armageddon in Retrospect | title_orig = <!--N/a--> | translator = <!--n/a--> | image = Armageddon in retrospect.jpg | caption = Cover of ''Armageddon in Retrospect'' | author = [[Kurt Vonnegut]] | illustrator = <!--n/a--> | cover_artist = | country = US | language = English | series = <!--n/a--> | subject = <!--n/a--> | genre = [[Fiction]], [[Anthology]] | publisher = [[G. P. Putnam's Sons]] | release_date = [[2008 in literature|2008]] | media_type = | pages = 234 | isbn = 978-0-399-15508-6 | preceded_by = | followed_by = [[Look at the Birdie]] }} '''''Armageddon in Retrospect''''' is a collection of [[short story|short stories]] and [[essay]]s about war and peace written by [[Kurt Vonnegut]]. It is the first [[List of works published posthumously|posthumous]] collection of his previously unpublished writings. The book includes an introduction by [[Mark Vonnegut]], a letter from Kurt to his family about his experiences as an American [[prisoner of war]] in Nazi Germany, and the fire-bombing of Dresden.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Blount, Jr.|first1=Roy|title=So It Goes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/04/books/review/Blount-t.html|accessdate=18 February 2017|publisher=''The New York Times''|date=May 4, 2008}}</ref> Like many of Vonnegut's other books, ''Armageddon in Retrospect'' is laden with handwritten quotations and rough drawings by the author.
