{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Ruderi di Gibellina.jpg | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Il Grande Cretto | artist=[[Alberto Burri]] | year=1984–2015 | type=Cement sculpture | height_metric=150 | width_metric=35000 | length_metric=28000 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Gibellina]], [[Sicily]] }}
The '''Cretto di Burri''' (crack of Burri) or Cretto di Gibellina (crack of Gibellina), also known as "The Great Cretto", is a landscape artwork which undertaken by [[Alberto Burri]] in 1984 and was left in an unfinished state in 1989 (due to lack of funds),<ref>http://www.burricentenario.com/home/iniziative-ed-eventi-del-centenario-di-burri/</ref><ref>http://www.gibellina.siciliana.it/pages/cretto.html</ref> based on the old city of [[Gibellina]]. The original city of Gibellina was completely destroyed in the [[1968 Belice earthquake]].<ref>http://www.palinsesti.org/2006/grande-cretto</ref> Gibellina has since been rebuilt, about 20&nbsp;km from the city's original location. In 2015 to mark what would have been Burri's one hundredth birthday the work was completed at last.<ref>http://www.abitare.it/en/habitat-en/landascape-design-en/2015/11/06/in-gibellina-the-cretto-by-burri-is-finished-after-30-years/?refresh_ce-cp</ref>
The work is the subject of a short documentary by the Dutch filmmaker Petra Noordkamp which was created as commissioned by the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] to be screened at the Alberto Burri retrospective held at the institution from October 9, 2015 until January 6, 2016.<ref>http://5dutchdaysnyc.org/petra-noordkamp-film-on-il-grande-cretto-di-gibellini/</ref>
